, yet built upon scholarship and theoretical contributions that ensure Infected Kin will remain relevant to anyone interested in anthropology, kinship, global health, and care. Supplementary teaching materials are available at: https://www.csbsju.edu/sociology/anthropology-teaching-resources/useful-resources/infected-kin-teaching-resources  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAIDS (Disease) in childrenzLesotho. 0aAIDS (Disease)zLesotho. 0aFamilieszLesotho. 0aKinshipzLesotho. 0aMedical anthropology. 0aOrphansxCarezLesotho. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aManderson, Lenore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGrath, Will, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065352640uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781978804784zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978804784423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781978804784.jpg  a978-3-11-065352-6  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK